The '''infraorbital vein''' arises on the face by the union of several tributaries. Accompanied by the [[infraorbital artery]] and the [[infraorbital nerve]], it passes posteriorly through the [[infraorbital foramen]], [[infraorbital canal]], and [[infraorbital groove]]. It drains through the [[inferior orbital fissure]] into the [[pterygoid venous plexus]]. It receives tributaries from structures that lie close to the floor of the orbit and communicates with the [[inferior ophthalmic vein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9KXRCwAAQBAJ|title=Clinical Anatomy of the Eye|first1=Richard S.|last1=Snell|first2=Michael A.|last2=Lemp|date=9 April 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|via=Google Books}}</ref>

